<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan-War     10-08 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan-War,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil War Ravages Civilian Life in Southern Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALAKAL, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Matchstick-thin, naked children with swollen bellies stand under a harsh sun, chewing dried, uncooked fish. Their emaciated elders sit with blank stares, gazing toward the horizon. Half the 50,000 people living in this wretched Nile riverport are seeking shelter in <LOCATION> Malakal </LOCATION> from the horrors of a seemingly interminable civil war, refugees in their own country. Sanitary services are non-existent, and malaria and typhoid run rampant. Those who are sick have but one dilapidated hospital to turn to, with only a handful of doctors and almost no medical supplies. <LOCATION> Malakal </LOCATION>, capital of the southern <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> region, is a microcosm of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s southland, an area the size of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> laid waste by 6 -LCB- years of warfare and famine. A massive international relief operation prevented a repeat of the mass starvation experienced in the summer of 1988. But the rebellion's accumulated effects continue to wreak havoc on the region's desperate civilians. Government troops control <LOCATION> Malakal </LOCATION>, 425 miles south of the capital, <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, as they do most southern population centers. Nevertheless, rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> stake out areas on its perimeter as freely as they move about in more than 90 percent of the southern countryside. Militarily, the war has basically been at a standstill for months. Both sides agreed in April to quiet their guns to let relief goods go through. A military junta took power in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> June 30, promising to end the war, and has extended the truce each month. The rebels have gone along. But political maneuvering over how and when to talk peace continues, leaving the people of <LOCATION> Malakal </LOCATION> and the rest of the south struggling, but surviving. `` People may think we're all dead,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Maker </PERSON>, a government employee, `` but we're still living, despite the war.'' A chieftain of the Shuluk tribe told a visiting reporter: `` Life is going on here. We are life. We are giving birth, and we are eating. Although very little.'' The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> says 250,000 southerners died a year ago of starvation or disease in a famine caused by the war. Other Western relief workers estimate the death toll at twice that. To prevent a recurrence, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agencies organized Operation Lifeline <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> to position 105,000 tons of relief goods in key transit points for distribution to displaced people after monsoon-like summer rains isolated them this year. Organizers say 80 percent of the goods was positioned in time. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON>, regional monitor of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, said government and rebels are negotiating the dispatch of a third convoy of <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> barges with additional relief for the Upper Nile. The program has had to overcome logistical and political problems, he said. There were too few workers for unloading the barges en route and inadequate storage facilities. Local officials complained about unfair distribution. As displaced people flooded the towns, the numbers of people who had to be cared for kept changing. <LOCATION> Malakal </LOCATION> still faces life-threatening problems, especially in health care. `` Malaria and typhoid are everywhere, and we have no chloroquine -LRB- malaria medicine -RRB- or syringes,'' said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Galwak </PERSON> <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, military governor for the <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION>. `` We have only one general practitioner, when we need at least 24. We have some 500 -LRB- doses -RRB- of medication, which would be consumed in one day if we were to use them, but we have more than 600 patients coming in every day.'' Doctors and nurses said the town's lone hospital has 14 badly equipped wards with about 500 beds. Hospital records show at least two deaths a day from malaria or typhoid. Hospital staff are helped by three doctors of the French organization <ORGANIZATION> Medicins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frontieres </ORGANIZATION> and some military doctors. `` These deaths are only the ones in the hospital,'' said one of the French physicians, who identified himself as Dr. <PERSON> Pathot </PERSON>. `` We have no car at all, nor an ambulance, so if somebody is going to die, he may do it before coming to us. `` We ca n't say how many die every day.'' As the civilian populace struggles to survive, the army has been trying to reopen the town's 10 schools, closed for almost three years. Two primary schools have been reopened. A reporter touring them found the classes had no desks, stools or blackboards. Children sat on the ground, their teachers instructing them to read and write by using the earth as a blackboard and a stick as chalk.
</TEXT>
