<HEAD>Disabled Guerrillas Leave For Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of 47 disabled guerrillas left late Saturday for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> under protection of the Mexican government and the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, government and airport officials said. The 47, mostly amputees, belong to the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. They occupied the capital's Metropolitan Cathedral for six weeks then on Tuesday moved into the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in their efforts to leave the country. In <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement the group, accompanied by two nurses, was headed for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. The statement said the group `` left tonight on a special <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> flight for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, where they have asked to be taken to receive special medical attention.'' Officials at <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s international airport said the 47 left on a plane chartered by the Mexican government. Officials from the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> or Salvadoran government would not speak to reporters Saturday. The guerrillas also were told not to speak to the press. But one guerrilla, identified only as <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, told reporters, `` We're going to leave for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, who lost a leg in combat, said the group hoped to receive medical care in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. It could not be determined whether the disabled men, most of them young, received political asylum in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Monsignor <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivero </PERSON> <PERSON> Damas </PERSON>, the archbishop of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, called the evacuation, `` one of the points of humanization in the conflict.'' Late last month, <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> <PERSON> Damas </PERSON> appealed for the guerrillas to vacate his church, saying: `` The cathedral is not a hotel.'' <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON>'s government said 2,000 soldiers, 500 guerrillas and 700 civilians have been disabled in combat during the more than nine years of civil war. Leftist rebels have fought the succession of U.S.-backed governments for nearly 10 years. Since 1984, 346 guerrillas have been evacuated to other countries, including <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The last evacuation occurred in May.
