<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Referendum, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0647,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Decide on Amendments Dealing with Highways, Black Judges</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES to RECAST throughout with vote count totals nearly complete,
details</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A plan to improve and expand <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s highways won solid approval from voters, but proposals to enhance blacks' voting power in electing judges were rejected in Saturday's statewide None of the 13 state amendments to the state constitution on the ballot drew much organized opposition. The only extensive campaigns were for passage of the highway plan; a proposal to make it easier for police to confiscate the property of suspected drug dealers and a measure to set aside at least $ 5 million a year in state mineral revenue to restore eroding wetlands. The drug confiscation and wetlands issues both passed easily. Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, who included the highway funding plan as part of a tax revision package that voters rejected April 29, said it would boost efforts to attract new industry to <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and create thousands of construction jobs. With about 94 percent of the votes counted, the amendment had the support of 430,791 voters, or 71 percent, and was opposed by 174,528, or 29 percent. The proposal would put the state's 16-cent motor fuel tax into a trust fund to be used solely for highways and public works projects. It included a 4-cent gasoline tax increase to finance $ 1.4 billion in transportation improvements, including four lanes for major highways and expansion of ports and airports. The two judicial amendments _ defeated by 3-to-1 margins _ would have added a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice and a majority black district in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> area, and created up to 35 black-majority sub-districts for district and appellate courts. The civil rights challenges that prompted the amendments came about because there are no blacks on the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, only one black among the state's 52 appellate court judges, and five black district court judges out of 192. Several tax-related amendments also were on the ballot, including measures to raise the automobile license plate fee; to allow cities and towns to raise property taxes; and to extend from five years to 10 years the current property tax assessment freeze for owners who expand or improve buildings in certain districts.
