<FIRST>u i AM-Pope-Asia 1stLd-Writethru a0515 10-08 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Asia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Appeals For End to Ideological Rifts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Sunday mass; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> appealed Sunday for an end to ideological divisions worldwide and said the bitter struggle that divides north and south <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> symbolized suffering. `` East is divided from west, north from south,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said at an open air mass attended by 700,000. He appealed for the world to give up mistrust, hostility and conflict `` to live in peace and brotherhood.'' `` The Korean nation is symbolic of a world divided and not yet able to become one in peace and justice,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said, speaking alternately in Korean and English. The vast crowd, many of whom had lined up before dawn, waved white Korean flags and some wept as the pope entered an immense plaza for the mass. Hundreds of singers burst into hymn as the pope walked along a red carpet toward a four-story stage and altar, tiered with thousands of red, white, yellow and pink flowers and flanked by colorful banners. Plain-clothed South Korean security agents carrying submachine guns ringed the stage, and 11,000 police were deployed on the outskirts of the plaza. Those who attended the mass had to pass through metal detectors. About 2,000 priests, aided by 2,000 women in traditional Korean gowns, served communion, while 1,200 white doves were released as a sign of peace. At an earlier meeting with President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, the pope asked the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> leader to make every effort to achieve full democracy and eradicate the nation's legacy of authoritarian rule, a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> spokesman said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> told <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> that <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Koreans </ORGANIZATION> want full democratic rights and freedoms, the spokesman said. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> began his <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> pilgrimage in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Saturday. About 1,000 dissidents and radical students staged an anti-government rally at <ORGANIZATION> Sogang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to urge the pope to speak out on human rights abuses in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. An equal number of riot police surrounded the campus, but made no move to halt Saturday's protest. The students dispersed peacefully after demanding the release of jailed dissidents, including South Korean clergymen charged with visiting <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> for unification talks. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> after for the first time flying across the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and sending greetings to Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in a sign of remarkably improved Vatican-Soviet relations. He expressed hope he would soon visit <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. He immediately took up the issue of Korean reunification, which has divided the influential <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> community in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Addressing himself to the `` dear people of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said: `` In the face of the tragic division which continues to separate your own people, do you not have the urgent mission to prove to a world torn by mistrust, strife and hatred that mankind does have the resources to end division and war, and to forge an enduring peace?'' The <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, divided in 1945, is the site of one of the world's most bitter ideological confrontations. The capitalist South and the totalitarian North, which fought to a bloody stalemate in the Korean War, clash frequently and m