<FIRST>r a AM-GeriatricJets 880   10-08 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Geriatric Jets, 880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Concern Over Aging Airliners Bringing New FAA Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is preparing orders that will force airlines to regularly strip the interiors of their aging jetliners for corrosion inspections. Rules are also being considered to require all new airliner models to undergo pressurized tests on a sample aircraft that would batter the fuselage with the equivalent of two lifetimes of takeoffs and landings. These and other steps to ensure the safety of airliners that are increasingly used long past their designed lifespans were presented at a three-day industry and government conference last week. More than 300 aviation experts at the second annual International Conference on Aging Aircraft viewed slides of deteriorating jetliners, discussed an array of sophisticated detection equipment and exchanged horror stories, including the supposed discovery of a dead frog in a corrosion-prone jetliner section now referred to as `` the guppy pond.'' With the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fleet of passenger jets exceeding 12 years old and expected to grow older as the demand pushes airlines to refurbish rather than retire their oldest models, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials disclosed plans for new `` airworthiness directives'' to deal with corrosion in <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747, 737, 727 and 707 jetliners. The orders are expected next month, to be followed in February 1990 by similar directives affecting <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas-built </ORGANIZATION> jets and later for other aircraft, said <PERSON> LeRoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Keith </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Certification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directorate </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> `` There are no plans for mandatory retirement ages, but the cost will be going up in maintaining aging aircraft,'' <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> said. The corrosion orders are based on the work of an industry-government task force that already has triggered sweeping changes in the way older airliners are kept safe. Both industry and government officials stress that none of the steps indicate that airliners now in service are unsafe but are an effort to ensure against failures before dangers arise. Since the task force was set up at the first aging airliner conference sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and the industry-backed <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> 16 months ago, the government has ordered mandatory replacements of parts on jetliners as they reach a set number of takeoffs and landings. Previously, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> ordered repetitive inspections, with replacements required only when problems were found. Those orders focused primarily on problems related to metal fatigue as an airliner is pressurized for flight and depressurized upon landing. The new directives, which are expected to be adopted in other countries where U.S.-built airliners fly, will require carriers to set up their own anti-corrosion programs, with inspections on various sections of each airliner at intervals ranging from three to eight years. Corrosion is more closely related than fatigue to chronological age, the quality of care the airliner is given, the environment in which it is flown, and conditions within the aircraft. Frequent coffee spills in the galley or regular hauling of fish or animal products in the cargo hold, for example, can accelerate corrosion. No airliner model is immune to deterioration, said government scientist <PERSON> Pin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>. `` Multiple-site damage is not isolated to one manufacturer or one model but may appear anywhere in the aging fleet,'' he said. Both <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> have conducted extensive tests on selected models to determine how many takeoffs and landings an airliner can undergo without damage. A DC-9 fuselage went through the equivalent of more than 200,000 flights with `` no evidence of multiple-site fatigue damage,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagemaier </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> engineer. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said rules requiring such testing for all new aircraft models are being drawn up and could affect future design. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has been calling for such tests to set design service life for airliners. <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> proposes that any extension of the service life be certified only after a tear-down inspection of a representative aircraft. J. <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marceau </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> corrosion expert, said more than 75 percent of corrosion problems been solved in new passenger planes rolling off the assembly line. `` We have the majority of problems licked with new design philosophies,'' he said. The new corrosion orders will classify damage at three levels, including the earliest signs, localized damage and extensive deterioration. `` An airline will have to open its planes up, inspect, repair anything that's found, report the findings to the government, apply corrosive-prevention compounds and then close it up,'' said <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schrader </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> aging aircraft program manager at the certification office in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. `` The goal is to require inspections frequently enough that eventually we wo n't find anything but level-one corrosion,'' he said. The orders could prove costly to some carriers, but <PERSON> Schrader </PERSON> said most major airlines already have anti-corrosion programs and the required inspections could be done along with other mandatory work. The goal is to find an inexpensive means of quickly checking whole airliners for both cracks and corrosion without tearing them apart. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> scientists indicated significant research still is needed, with a number of methods being tested and used in current inspections. But <PERSON> Schrader </PERSON> said the only acceptable detection device for the mandatory corrosion inspections is likely to be the human eye.
</TEXT>
