<SECOND>AM-German Reunification, 960</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Raise Question of German Reunification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dramatic rush of refugees from East to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is causing officials to take a new look at a prospect once considered remote _ the reunification of that divided country. While experts say the formation of one <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is still not in the cards for the near future, it is a possibility that can no longer be dismissed as very remote. Any concrete moves toward reunification are likely to worry people in countries that have twice in this century faced Germans on the battlefield. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> G.H </PERSON>. <PERSON> Seitz </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> affairs, reaffirmed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for eventual unification in testimony before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee last week, but added that it must be approached with caution because of `` a history in which the unification of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> led to instability and war.'' `` The reunification of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> raises the prospect of major changes on the continent, and therefore is something we have to look at very carefully,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, D-Ind., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Affairs subcommittee on <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> `` We have kind of paid lip service to it without really thinking about the implications of it,'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I think a lot of countries have done that.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> governments have long been on record in favor of reuniting <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which was split into two countries after the Allied victory in World War II and the onset of the Cold War between East and West. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said in an interview, `` A lot of people in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, most West European countries, have strong emotional reservations'' about reunification. `` They have n't had to deal with those reservations until very recently.'' Like others interviewed, this official said, `` My own expectation is that reunification is still a good many years away.'' But he added, `` If we had been talking a couple of months ago, I would have said it was very, very remote. The fact that things are moving in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> has obviously changed the picture.'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said, `` I do n't think reunification of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is going to come about in 1990, but it is clearly going to be put on the agenda now and discussed much more.'' So far this year, more than 120,000 East Germans have reached <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where they are granted automatic citizenship. The exodus has been helped by the decision of the reformist regime in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to open its borders. West German Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> has spoken recently of the possibility of a German confederation, a step short of complete unity. <PERSON> Ingrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Stahmer </PERSON>, deputy mayor of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, asked about reunification on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America'' Thursday, said, `` We do n't see reunification in that we would form one state again, but I think that we must come closer ... I think that we will come together on the way to -LRB- a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' But East German historian <PERSON> Siegfried </PERSON> <PERSON> Prokop </PERSON>, asked on the same program whether unification was in prospect, replied, `` Absolutely not. It's a dream of the ... reactionary forces in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.'' Faced with reform movements in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, the Soviets are anxious to keep <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> in their orbit. The country has a standard of living that is the envy of many of its East Bloc neighbors, although it remains far below <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s. Experts said one of the major obstacles to unification is the absence in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> of a strong opposition such as the Solidarity union which has formed the new government in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> or the movements that are bringing about broad political reforms in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. `` I think we are far from a place where this East German regime or its likely successors are going to move in that direction,'' said <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Sonnenfeldt </PERSON>, Berlin-born guest scholar in foreign policy studies at the liberal-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> and former <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> counselor. `` <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, in this situation, I do n't think has very many good choices,'' said <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>. `` There seems to be no way out,'' said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, director of foreign policy and defense studies for the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. Still, said <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, `` We see the possibility for the first time of revisiting the German question in a real kind of way. I would have said a year ago, ` Not in my lifetime.' I am beginning to think, given how swift the events were in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and what has happened with the refugees, that it could happen a lot sooner than a lot of people think.'' <PERSON> Sonnenfeldt </PERSON> said the recent developments `` certainly have put that subject on people's agenda again.'' `` If one means re-establishing the previous German <PERSON> Reich </PERSON>, even in a somewhat smaller territory, I think that is probably not in the cards for any time soon,'' the former <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said. `` I think there is a lot of concern in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> about the reconstitution of something that resembles the previous <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> that existed from 1871 on and especially in the Hitlerian period,'' he said. `` I think in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this is less of a factor, but I am sure there are particular groups in this country who would have strong feelings about it.'' <PERSON> Said </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, `` It raises maybe concern, but concern only in the sense that we are not sure where it might end up. And it could end up in a number of different ways, some of which could not be in our interest.''
