<HEAD>Cavazos Calls for Study Of Indians' Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-College Curriculum Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> criticized the government's schooling of Native Americans on Sunday and called for a study that he said `` could prove revolutionary for Indian education.'' <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> used the 21st <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, to call for a `` federally directed gathering campaign'' and a special task force `` involving the participation of Native American citizens and educators'' to analyze the problems that Native Americans face with education. A copy of his speech was released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said the results of the survey he called for could have the same impact as the a 1983 government general education report that `` shocked the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public and led to the education reform movement that has come to many areas of the country.'' `` I see this developing into an ` Indian Nations At Risk' study, which will follow the path laid out by the landmark study of the national education structure, ` A Nation At Risk,''' said <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON>. The education secretary said <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> has agreed `` that we must move in this direction and the two departments, Education and Interior, must work together to address the needs in Indian education.'' <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> are the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's only Hispanic Cabinet members. The education secretary, a Texan like President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, was first appointed by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as the first Hispanic to the Cabinet. Briefly recounting the history of Native Americans, <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said, `` Long before the appearance of the Anglo on the shores of the North American continent, you nations had instituted systems of education. `` The first treaty signed with the newly independent <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1794 by the <LOCATION> Oneida </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tuscarora </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION> tribes provided for Indian education,'' he said. `` The respect for knowledge held by Native Americans makes the failures of effective education policies for the Indian nations these past two centuries all the more tragic,'' said <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON>, noting an article that described `` the history of Indian education -LRB- as one -RRB- of crossed purposes and unfulfilled hopes that is still unfolding today.'' An <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> study of high school sophomores found that from 1980 through 1986, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Alaskan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natives </ORGANIZATION> dropped out at more than double the rate for the whole test group. Native American students are likely to be labeled handicapped or learning disabled, the study said. Eleven percent of Indian sophomores in public and private schools were enrolled in special education programs and 36 percent were classified as having some form of handicap. In comparison, 9 percent blacks and 7 percent of Hispanics were in special programs. <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said the 1980 census found only about 8 percent of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> 25 years and older had completed four years of college. He said a recent study revealed that nearly three out of four American Indian college students do not earn degrees. The statistics are due partly to the government's failed attempts to at first assimilate Native Americans and then to urbanize them, he said. Now, <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said, the federal government is trying to replace assimilation with self-determination. He said these efforts are being bolstered by the administration's education initiatives like choice _ allowing parents to decide where to send their children to school _ and school-based management, where principals, teachers, parents and students set their own curricula, agendas and plans. He said the study he wants must provide a complete review of government programs that affect Indian education. The focus will be on the cost effectiveness of current efforts, as well as developing cooperation between the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> and the Education Department.
