<HEAD>Jogger's Injury Inspires Central Park Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly six months after the brutal rape of a Central Park jogger, the 29-year-old woman is recovering and sending messages to a group of fellow runners who are helping make the park safer for everyone who uses its green expanse. Police have beefed up park security and volunteers are patrolling the park, offering partners for runners and bringing groups of them together for safer exercise. `` This is how good comes from bad,'' said <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Road Runners Safety Program. The jogger, an investment banker, was attacked by a mob of teen-agers as she ran alone in the northern part of the park, late in the evening of April 19. When police found the woman hours later, she was in a coma and had lost three-quarters of her blood. Paramedics did not expect her to live. She remained in critical condition until May 1, when she appeared to raise her eyebrows as her name was called and raised her hand. She was walking a bit when she was moved June 7 to <LOCATION> Gaylord </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Wallingford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. By midsummer, she reportedly was classified as a 7 on a recovery scale of 1 to 8 Patients must reach level 8 to live independently. She was able to read novels, relearn basic math skills and call colleagues at <LOCATION> Solomon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brothers </LOCATION>, where she had worked before the attack. <PERSON> Gaylord </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Brass </PERSON> said last week that the jogger was `` making good progress, doing well.'' She would not elaborate. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Runners </ORGANIZATION>, said he had never met the injured jogger but received communicatio