<HEAD>Armani Brings Back the Hippies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spring 1990 will mark the rebirth of flower power, at least in the fashion world. <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>, who opened the Italian spring-summer ready-to-wear shows Sunday with his <ORGANIZATION> Emporio </ORGANIZATION> line, called on the young to recall the hippie dress code of their parents _ gypsy skirts and shawls, vests, tattered jeans, oversized shirts and jackets, clumpy sandals. For beach boys and girls, <PERSON> Armani </PERSON> drew inspiration from the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> with fishnet and burlap his-and-her sarongs and diaper shorts. Italian beaches have long bade farewell to the bikini of the 1960s, giving way to whole suits for women and surf shorts for men. <PERSON> Armani </PERSON> takes the look a step further by delving into grandma's trunk for those Great Gatsby striped tank suits A gasp went up among Americans attending the early morning show in the theater of <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>'s downtown palazzo at the parade of bare-breasted woman surrounded by bare-chested men, all wearing <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>'s jeans. Europeans, accustomed to topless bathing, did n't bat an eyelash The blazer king likes his jackets long and light, with a curved front like a tulip petal, reminiscent of designs several seasons ago by <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Romeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Gigli </PERSON>. There was a touch of <PERSON> Gigli </PERSON> too in the faded pastel shades of the collection and the rounded uneven hemlines of skirts and dresses. For summer <PERSON> Armani </PERSON> hikes his hemlines way above his demure winter length. Lightweight pantsuits with ample jackets and baggy trousers and a series of cool cotton jumpsuits are sure to attract summer city dwellers. Another fashion favorite of the younger set, <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Moschino </PERSON>, also showed Sunday morning. What attracts the young in <LOCATION> Moschino </LOCATION> is his irony toward fashion and the fashion world at large. During his shows he likes to hide his own beautiful clothes under exaggerations of other designers' embellishments Thus he once based an entire show on headgear from stovepipes to teddy bears, mocking <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacroix </PERSON>. At every show he makes a point of ladening his evening wear with heavy gold chains, a Chanel trademark. <PERSON> Moschino </PERSON> also likes to poke fun at people who live by labels, often sewing his own label on the outside of an outfit. Last season he designed a jacket with the words `` very expensive jacket'' stitched on the back in gold letters. For spring-summer 1990, <PERSON> Moschino </PERSON> also flirt with the new hippie trend in a series of multicolored gypsy skirts, jeans outfits and Mexican-style long vests, but the bulk of his collection was based on an evening look of basic black and gold. His most astonishing outfit was a three-piece suit _ jacket, brassiere and short skirt _ in glimmery gold fabric, with lavish gold jewelry and a gold chain belt. His most ironic style was a floor-length black chiffon gown with the letters VIP in gold down the front, with the V incorporated in the neckline. Over the next five days, forty of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s top ready-to-wear designers, including <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>, <PERSON> Versace </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Krizia </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Biagiotti </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Missoni </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fendi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ferre </PERSON> will present their styles for next year's warmer weather. Along with beautiful clothes the fashion crowd will be treated to a night at the famed <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION> house for a performance by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s Bolshoi theater.
