would be an important boost for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> should it try to tap the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bond market as part of its modernization drive. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> returned to foreign bond markets for the first time in 70 years when it sold a debt issue in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> in January 1988. Since then it has sold five more bond issues in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, mostly to banks, for a total of about $ 850 million worth of borrowing, according to S & amp; P. But it has yet to attempt a bond issue in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. One reason is that it must first settle about $ 193 million worth of bonds sold by Czarist <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government to help finance <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> participation in World War I. After the 1917 revolution, the new Soviet government repudiated the bonds and has yet to make good on them. Under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law, the Soviets are barred from selling bonds here until they settle this old debt. A 1986 settlement with <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> over a similar Czarist bond offering bodes well for negotiations now under way with the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bonds, S & amp; P said. The credit rating agency said many problems stand in the way of assessing the investment risk of Soviet bonds. Among them are the unreliable and incomplete nature of Soviet government statistics, lack of comparability between some Soviet and Western economic data, and the lack of firm figures on total Soviet borrowings in the West. `` Right now, analyzing the Soviet economy is a game of estimations,'' said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P analyst. `` It's a new frontier to some degree.'' <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> declined to comment on whether <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> officials have agreed to cooperate with a credit analysis should <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P decide to do one. But, he said, `` It's a little difficult to obtain that information without being able to talk to the government about it.'' A credit rating is important because it helps investors determine the chances that their money will be repaid when a bond come due. It also gives them an idea of the rate of interest they should require to tie up their money. Ironically, the attempts of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to restructure his nation's economy, called perestroika, could harm the country's once-sterling credit standing among Western bankers, who have loaned it money since the early 1970s. With perestroika has come instability and an economic downturn. `` The system that was in place gave bankers a lot of confidence in the Soviet government's ability to repay their obligations,'' <PERSON> Bates </PERSON> said. However, he said, it appears that much of the Soviet government's ability to adjust the nation's balance-of-payments figures in order to repay foreign debt remain in place. A book published earlier this year is skeptical of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s recent Western borrowing. `` The Coming Soviet Crash: <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s Desperate Pursuit of Credit in Western Financial Markets,'' contends that Soviet economic statistics are extremely unreliable and that assumptions about the nation's ability to repay its debt may be erroneous. The author, <ORGANIZATION> Hoover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> researcher <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON>, also criticizes the popular belief that the West is accelerating <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms by loaning money. She contends that instead of reducing military spending or making other tough economic choices, the Soviets are looking abroad for the cash to pay for perestoika while preserving their military might. S & amp; P's chief competitor, <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has not rated the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> either, but it recently released a credit study of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, another East bloc nation undergoing economic liberalization. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> also has been selling bonds in the West. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s analyst <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Bemmelen </PERSON> said obtaining the required information about <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> took longer than the time spent for similar evaluations of Western nations. But he said his company is confident about the results. Though there were problems in obtaining government data about the domestic Hungarian economy, he said, `` most of the determinants of the creditworthiness are really in its relationship to Western countries.'' That type of information is available from several sources, he said, including international banks and exporters and importers. But <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Bemmelen </PERSON> said he could foresee additional problems in rating the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, such as valuing its huge gold holdings. The Soviet government does not disclose that amount.
