<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A vandal threw paint on windows and walls of the Jewish State Theater over the weekend in an attack linked to the dispute over a Roman Catholic convent at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>, police reported. The vandal painted the message, `` This is for the convent.'' Worshippers saw the damage as they arrived Sunday night to mark the beginning of Yom Kippur, the most solemn Jewish holiday, at <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s only synagogue that is next to the theater. Police said the blue paint had been splattered on the building Saturday. The theater, created by the state shortly after World War II, presents plays in Yiddish, preserving a cultural remnant of what was once one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s most vibrant Jewish communities. `` A lot of nasty and unexpected things have happened recently,'' said Rabbi <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Joskowitz </PERSON>, a survivor of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> who emigrated this year from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to serve as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s only rabbi `` Synagogue windows have been broken in <LOCATION> Lublin </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Czestochowa </PERSON>,'' he said. The rabbi said the violence was a result of controversy over the convent of Carmelite nuns on the perimeter of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> concentration camp in southern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Jewish leaders have demanded that the convent be removed, saying Christian symbols are intrusive at a place where 2.5 million Jews were murdered. Catholic Cardinal <PERSON> Franciszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Macharski </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> agreed in 1987 to relocate the convent, but a 1989 deadline was not met and the Polish church said the agreement was not valid. After the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> intervened in the dispute in August Polish bishops agreed again to move the nuns to an international prayer center. On Saturday, the Polish episcopate issued a statement saying it hoped the prayer center will `` contribute to development of Christian-Jewish dialogue in the spirit of mutual respect and understanding of the importance of the <ORGANIZATION> Auschwitz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp ... for Poles, Jews and other nations.'' The Jewish demands angered some Poles who said the nuns harmed no one and should be allowed to pray for the tens of thousands of non-Jewish victims killed at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>.
