<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Arab petroleum-producing countries were urged by experts Sunday to increase exploration in order to boost reserves and prevent shortages in the next century. Current Arab oil reserves plus recoverable reserves and anticipated discoveries can satisfy oil demand until 2020, said <PERSON> Abdul-Aziz </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Wattari </PERSON>, assistant secretary-general of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries. `` But a gap between supply and demand will then occur unless new reserves are discovered to help meet the accelerating demand for energy from hydrocarbons,'' <PERSON> Wattari </PERSON> said in an inaugural speech of a four-day seminar in <LOCATION> Abu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dhabi </LOCATION>. The four-day seminar on `` Deep Formations in the Arab Countries: Hydrocarbon Potential and Exploration Techniques,'' is the first of its kind in the Gulf and was organized by <ORGANIZATION> OAPEC </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Abu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dhabi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wattari </PERSON> told over 70 participants that world energy consumption has been increasing in recent years and was expected to continue rising in the coming years `` Increases in oil production and reserves should match that. And some oil experts forecast that oil production will peak at 75 million barrels per day in the year 2010,'' he said. Daily world oil output currently is 62 million barrels, of which the Arab world accounts for roughly 18 million barrels. He urged <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states to make use of new advanced exploration techniques developed in Western countries. <ORGANIZATION> ADNOC </ORGANIZATION> General Manager <PERSON> Sohail </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Mazroui </PERSON>, backing <PERSON> Wattari </PERSON>'s call, said expanded oil exploration was `` essential in order to guarantee the continuation of petroleum supplies at their current level. Experts believe there will be an increased global dependence on Arab oil as reserves of other oil-producing nations will vanish in the future.''
</TEXT>
