<DATELINE>LOGAN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> promised Sunday that the union's bitter strike against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will continue until a contract is reached. `` How long are we willing to go? One day longer than <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> told a solidarity rally attended by 1,500 miners and retirees and their families. The <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> has been striking <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> since April in a contract dispute over health and insurance benefits. Miners from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> attended the rally pledging to continue selective strikes against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> and other companies the union says supplies the nation's second largest coal exporter. Last week, a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> judge fined the union $ 6.9 million for illegal strike activities, bringing the total fines assessed during the strike to more than $ 30 million. But <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> said the union has enough money to continue the strike. `` We have ample resources to take care of our strikers indefinitely,'' said <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON>. He added that striking miners now are eligible to apply for $ 1,000 interest-free loans from the union. Last week the 80,000-member <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> rejoined the 14 million-member <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> after a 40-year separation. <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> said the affiliation merely formalized a working cooperation the miners' union has had with the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>.
