<HEAD>Generic Drug Maker Complies With FDA Call To Recall Medication</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pharmaceutical maker on Sunday voluntarily began the recall of a generic antibiotic used to treat urinary tract infections a day after the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> requested the action. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> contends that <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Copiague </LOCATION>, cheated on product safety tests when it submitted the drug, nitrofurantoin, for <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approval <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON>, president of the company, said in a statement that the recall of the 100 mg capsules was in response to questions raised by the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION> is concerned first with the ongoing well-being of the people who use our drugs,'' <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON> said. `` The charges that have been made against this product and our company warrant this cautious move on our part while we investigate to determine where the truth lies.'' An <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> investigation found indications that <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION> substituted the brand name drug Macrodantin for its generic version in tests three years ago to win approval of the generic product, <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Nesbit </PERSON> said. `` We believe that this occurrence is not of <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION>'s doing,'' <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON> said, adding that the product tested by the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> was not the same product it provided for laboratory testing. Because of the evidence of a substitution, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> contends it is not possible to determine whether the <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION> product is equivalent to the brand-name product, which is made by <ORGANIZATION> Norwich-Eaton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION>, which is the largest of the generic drug makers under <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> scrutiny, won approval for its generic version of nitrofurantoin in June 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION>'s product is the only generic drug approved as therapeutically equivalent to Macrodantin, although other dosage forms of nitrofurantoin are available. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> also is investigating other generic drugs made by <ORGANIZATION> Bolar </ORGANIZATION> as part of its probe of more than a dozen generic drug companies in the wake of allegations of fraud and corruption within the industry and <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s generic drug division.
